The paper deals with a problem in computational geometry, specifically the intersection of line segments with disks. This suggests that cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is a likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the geometric Hitting Set problem, which is a well-known problem in computational complexity theory, indicating that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) are also possible sub-categories. The use of planar graphs and their properties, such as outerplane, Gabriel, and Delaunay graphs, suggests that cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the time and space complexity bounds of the algorithms suggest that cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) may also be a possible sub-category.
